1
00:00:08,834 --> 00:00:13,053
Edward Tufte is a seminal figure on how
to design visual displays of quantitative

2
00:00:13,053 --> 00:00:13,869
information.

3
00:00:13,869 --> 00:00:17,327
In fact, this is the title of
my favorite book of his, and

4
00:00:17,327 --> 00:00:21,030
I highly encourage you
to check out his work.

5
00:00:21,030 --> 00:00:24,920
In this book, he introduces two
interesting graphical heuristics,

6
00:00:24,920 --> 00:00:26,910
the data-ink ratio and chart junk.

7
00:00:28,230 --> 00:00:30,090
First, what's a heuristic?

8
00:00:30,090 --> 00:00:34,390
A heuristic is a process or rule that is
meant to guide you in decision making.

9
00:00:34,390 --> 00:00:40,120
Is by definition not known to be optimal
or perfect, but to be practical in nature.

10
00:00:40,120 --> 00:00:44,050
Heuristics are meant to be followed until
you've a reason to deviate from them.

11
00:00:44,050 --> 00:00:46,933
Tufte's first graphical
heuristic is data-ink ratio.

12
00:00:46,933 --> 00:00:52,350
Tufte defines data-ink as
the non-erasable core of a graphic.

13
00:00:52,350 --> 00:00:58,550
The non-redundant ink arranged in response
to variation in the numbers represented.

14
00:00:58,550 --> 00:01:03,210
In other words, the data-ink is essential
to the sense-making process for

15
00:01:03,210 --> 00:01:04,130
a given variable.

16
00:01:05,680 --> 00:01:09,330
Tufte defines the data-ink
ratio as the amount of data-ink

17
00:01:09,330 --> 00:01:13,060
divided by the total ink
required to print the graphic.

18
00:01:13,060 --> 00:01:16,610
Now I don't think that he's actually
suggesting we measure the amount of ink

19
00:01:16,610 --> 00:01:20,530
laid down on the page, but
instead is suggesting that we remove those

20
00:01:20,530 --> 00:01:23,500
elements which don't add new
information to the graphic.

21
00:01:24,780 --> 00:01:28,764
Perhaps one of the best known examples
showing data-ink reduction was done by

22
00:01:28,764 --> 00:01:31,964
Darkhorse Analytics,
an information, visualization, and

23
00:01:31,964 --> 00:01:35,440
design company in Edmonton,
Alberta, Canada.

24
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:39,890
They've put together four examples of
how the data-ink ratio can be approved.

25
